Quoted By: >>66448858 >>66448925 >>66448931
>>66447832
The technique being used in the Spiderverse films, as well as Puss in Boots: The Last Wish is known in the business as "animating on the 1s/2s/3s." Essentially hang frames interpolated into a sequence of smoother playback by a rate of 1, 2 or 3 elapsed frames per unit of animation. Originally a cost-cutting method, more companies and animators have adopted it for stylistic purposes since it helps the viewer define keyframes and thus allows the rigging process to simultaneously minimize complexity in a scene while allowing for more attention to model detail.

It isn't supposed to be realistic when used voluntarily, rather, it attempts to provide a certain tangibility to 2D or 3D actions; giving them weight. Hit stun in fighting games is one of the most popular citations for this particularly reason.
